<task id="AIPU2-066" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Latency Monitoring with Azure Monitor Metrics</title>
    <phase>3</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, monitoring, observability</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-061</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    The agent pipeline now has a clear structure (AIPU2-061) with measurable latency boundaries:
    Time-to-First-Token (TTFT), Time-Between-Tokens (TBT), Time-to-Last-Token (TTLT), and the
    prompt token count feeding the model tier routing decision. This task instruments those
    boundaries with OpenTelemetry metrics exported to Azure Monitor, adds alert thresholds
    (TTFT greater than 1.5s, prompt tokens greater than 9000), and creates a dashboard. Route
    layer distribution (which model tier handled each request) must also be tracked so the
    CapabilityRouter's tier assignment can be validated in production.
  </prompt>
  <role>DevOps/SRE developer with OpenTelemetry, Azure Monitor, and Application Insights experience.</role>
  <goal>
    TTFT, TBT, TTLT, prompt token count, and route layer distribution are tracked as Azure Monitor
    metrics. Alerts fire when TTFT exceeds 1.5 seconds or prompt tokens exceed 9000. A dashboard
    is created and accessible in the dev Azure Monitor workspace.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>docs/guides/AI-MONITORING-DASHBOARD.md</file>
      <file>docs/guides/MONITORING-AND-ALERTING-GUIDE.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read AI-MONITORING-DASHBOARD.md and MONITORING-AND-ALERTING-GUIDE.md to understand existing metric naming conventions, OTEL setup, and dashboard tooling in use.</step>
    <step>Add OTEL Histogram instruments: ai.chat.ttft (milliseconds), ai.chat.tbt (milliseconds), ai.chat.ttlt (milliseconds), ai.chat.prompt_tokens (count).</step>
    <step>Add OTEL Counter instrument: ai.chat.route_tier with dimension model_tier (e.g., "fast", "balanced", "deep") so route layer distribution is trackable.</step>
    <step>Record TTFT at the point the first token byte is written to the SSE response stream; TBT between each subsequent token; TTLT when the done event is emitted.</step>
    <step>Record prompt_tokens and model_tier from the CapabilityRouter's resolution result (available post AIPU2-061).</step>
    <step>Configure Azure Monitor alert rules: TTFT P95 greater than 1500ms (severity 2), prompt_tokens P95 greater than 9000 (severity 3).</step>
    <step>Create an Azure Monitor workbook or dashboard with panels: TTFT/TBT/TTLT percentile charts (P50, P95, P99), prompt token distribution histogram, route tier pie chart, active alert list.</step>
    <step>Verify metrics appear in Application Insights Live Metrics and custom metrics blade in the dev environment.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>TTFT, TBT, TTLT, prompt_tokens, and route_tier metrics are emitted via OTEL and visible in Azure Monitor.</criterion>
    <criterion>Alert rule for TTFT P95 greater than 1500ms is configured and testable.</criterion>
    <criterion>Alert rule for prompt_tokens P95 greater than 9000 is configured and testable.</criterion>
    <criterion>Dashboard or workbook with latency percentiles, token distribution, and tier distribution panels exists in the dev workspace.</criterion>
    <criterion>Metric naming follows existing conventions documented in AI-MONITORING-DASHBOARD.md.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
